    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "why would you call it a goblin though? i just meant it's a broken machine. can you just tell me how to check if the capacitor is actually the problem?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the goblin overload! I can certainly help you diagnose that humming noise without the extra goblin metaphors. Here is how to check if the capacitor is the problem:\n\n1.  **Safety First:** Turn off the power to the AC unit at the circuit breaker before touching anything.\n2.  **Locate the Capacitor:** It is usually a cylindrical canister with two wires attached, often mounted on the blower motor or near the contactor.\n3.  **Visual Inspection:** Look for bulging, leaking oil, or burnt marks on the casing. If it looks damaged, it is likely bad.\n4.  **Multimeter Test:** Set your multimeter to measure capacitance (Farads). Disconnect one wire from the capacitor and touch the probes to the terminals. Compare the reading to the rating printed on the capacitor itself. If the reading is significantly lower than the rated value, the capacitor is failing.\n\nIf the capacitor is good, the issue might be with the motor windings or the fan belt. If you are unsure about testing with a multimeter, it is always safer to call a professional HVAC technician.",
